{{Infobox climber | name = Kim Chang-ho | image = | image_size = <!--Only for images narrower than 220 pixels.--> | alt = | caption = | nickname = | nationality = South Korean | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = {{death date and given age|2018|10|12|49|df=y}} | death_place = Nepal | residence = | education = | occupation = | height = <!-- "X cm" or "X ft Y in" (conversions are automatic) --> | weight = <!-- "X kg" or "X lb" (conversions are automatic) --> | website = | typeofclimber = Mountaineering | highestgrade = | highestredpoint = | highestonsight = | knownfor = [[Eight-thousander#Climbers with verified ascents|Eight-thousander world record]] | firstascents = Himjung (7,092m); Batura II (7,762m) | majorascents = All 14 [[Eight-thousander|eight-thousanders]] | worlds = | updated = }}
'''Kim Chang-ho''' ({{lang-ko|김창호}}) was a South Korean mountain climber. Kim began climbing after reading about [[Alexander the Great]]'s exploits.<ref name="BMC"/>
In 2012, he won the Piolets d'or Asia award with An Chi-young when they made the first ever ascent of Himjung (7,092m) in Nepal; the [[British Mountaineering Council]] noted that, "Kim also made the first ascent of 7,762m Batura II. Together with Batura I West (7,775m), which remains virgin, Batura II was one of the highest unclimbed named summits in the [[Karakoram]] (and indeed Asia)".<ref name="BMC"/>
In 2013, he became the first Korean to climb all of the world's [[Eight-thousander| 14 mountains over 8,000 metres]] without using supplementary oxygen;<ref name="The Korea Times 21 May 2013">{{cite news |last= Kwon |first= Ji-youn | authorlink= |title= Kim scales 14 Himalaya peaks without oxygen tanks|url= http://m.koreatimes.co.kr/pages/article.asp?newsIdx=136095| date= 21 May 2013|newspaper= [[The Korea Times]] |location= | accessdate= 13 October 2018 }}</ref> in doing so he also set the record for completing the feat in the shortest time.<ref name="BBC News 13 October 2018">{{cite web | title= Nepal storm kills climbers on Himalayan peak Gurja |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-45848535| author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date= 13 October 2018 | website= [[BBC News Online]] | accessdate= 13 October 2018 }}</ref> His new world record of seven years, 10 months and six days was over a month quicker than the previous one, held by [[Jerzy Kukuczka]] of Poland.<ref name="BMC">{{cite web | title= Korean Everest Sea to Summit marred by tragedy| url= https://www.thebmc.co.uk/korean-everest-sea-to-summit-marred-by-tragedy | last= Griffin| first= Lindsay| date= 27 May 2013 | publisher= [[British Mountaineering Council]] | accessdate= 13 October 2018 }}</ref> Unusually, Kim used an "eco-friendly" approach, taking 60 days to reach the [[Everest Base Camp|Mount Everest base camp]] using "kayak, bicycle and foot" rather than flying to [[Lukla]].<ref name="The Korea Times 21 May 2013"/>
He was killed, along with several others including fellow South Korean climbers and local mountain guides, in [[Nepal]] in October, 2018, when a snowstorm destroyed the 3500m-altitude base camp beneath Mount Gurja in the [[Dhaulagiri]].<ref name="NYT">{{cite news |author1= Bhadra Sharma |author2= Kai Schultz | author3= Choe Sang-Hun | title= Snowstorm Kills at Least 8 Climbers in Nepal|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/13/world/asia/nepal-climbers-himalaya-mountains.html | date= 13 October 2018| newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |location=New York City| accessdate= 13 October 2018 }}</ref>
